article.headline: Third-ranked Tennessee struggles early
article.linkText: Lady Vols knock out Auburn in SEC quarterfinals
article.story:
NORTH LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) -- Auburn turned out to be just as
feisty as Tennessee had feared.

	   The third-ranked Lady Vols struggled against Auburn's trapping
zone defense for much of the game before finally pulling away to a
66-51 victory Friday in the Southeastern Conference tournament
quarterfinals.

	   "I enjoyed the second half a whole lot more than the first
half,'' Tennessee coach Pat Summitt said.

	   "We dug ourselves in a hole in the first half behind Auburn's
great defense. We were more patient offensively and got some
reversals (in the second half). We were a two-pass-and-shoot team
in the first half.''

	   Down by nine in the second half, Tennessee (27-3) held Auburn to
no field goals and just two free throws in the final 6:45 to
survive a major scare and avoid its earliest exit in the SEC
tournament since a quarterfinal loss to Arkansas in 1993.

	   Kara Lawson and Gwen Jackson led Tennessee with 17 points each,
Lawson getting 14 in the second half and Jackson 13. Jackson also
grabbed 12 rebounds, while Tasha Butts added 15 points and 11
rebounds to go with some tough defense.

	   "Everybody steps up for them,'' Auburn coach Joe Ciampi said.
"You have to stop their players and we felt that was Jackson and
Lawson. We wanted someone else to step up and I guess that Butts
answered the call.''

	   Auburn (18-11) lost to Tennessee by three and nine points in the
regular season and gave the Lady Vols a hard time again. The Tigers
made Tennessee take difficult shots, cut off passing lanes and
forced 11 first-half turnovers.

	   Tennessee began the second half trailing 31-22 and was down
39-30 after Natasha Brackett's 3-pointer with 14:47 left. It was
the biggest deficit the Lady Vols had faced in the second half
since their 76-55 loss to Duke on Nov. 24.

	   But Tennessee eventually started to find openings in the zone.
The Lady Vols used their offensive rebounding to get numerous
second- and third-chance shots and went on a 9-0 run with less than
nine minutes remaining to finally take control.

	   "We were not excited about playing that team a third time,''
Summitt said. "If you watched that game today, you understand why.
They are one of the best defensive teams in the country.''

	   A big key for Tennessee was shutting down Brackett after she
scored 17 points in the first half on 7-for-10 shooting, including
three 3-pointers. Hounded mostly by Butts, Bracket was 2-for-8 in
the second half and finished with 22 points.

	   Tia Miller scored 13 for Auburn, which shot just 7-of-30 in the
second half.

	   Outrebounded by two at halftime, Tennessee finished with a 50-37
advantage on the boards, with Jackson getting 12 and Butts 11. The
Lady Vols had 26 offensive rebounds, which led to 20 second-chance
points.

	   "I think that's the one thing the coaches impressed on us,''
Lawson said. "Auburn might not beat you on the first shot, but
they will on the second and third shot.

	   "I think the first possession of the second half we scored on a
second-chance opportunity and that was indicative of how we played
the rest of the way.''

	   Tennessee took its first lead since it was 16-14 when Loree
Moore hit a baseline jumper with 9:42 left to make it 46-45. Auburn
got the lead right back on Nicole Louden's jumper, but that was the
last time the Tigers were ahead.

	   Shyra Ely hit two free throws to start Tennessee's decisive run.
Jackson then beat Auburn down the floor for a layup, Butts made a 3
from the left wing and Ely scored on a putback to make it 55-47.

	   Brackett scored on a follow shot to cut the lead to 55-49, but
the Tigers didn't make another basket, and Tennessee finished the
game with an 11-2 run.

	   "I think they just outhustled us, that's all,'' Brackett said.
"I didn't see anything different in the second half.''
